  ---
  Two Metric Cards

  Chosen: Training Intensity + Weekly Km

  Why Training Intensity (not Load Ratio): The ratio is the right data but "Load Ratio: 1.12×" is jargon. Renaming to
  "Training Intensity" and expressing value as "+12% vs baseline" is immediately interpretable by any runner.

  Why Weekly Km: Every runner already tracks this. It anchors the abstract TSS to something concrete. No explanation
  required for what it measures.

  Why not Injury Risk as a card: Too alarming as a top-level default. Belongs below fold, shown only when risk is
  elevated. Not showing it when risk is low wastes the slot; showing it always normalises alarm.

  Why not Race Readiness: Unreliable before an 8-week baseline; misleading for beginners.

